Observation Details: Jay movement continued throughout the day, with birds still going over the house further inland later on.  None of the birds could be attributed as being 'in off the sea', all being seen south of the A149.  Shortly after arriving I could see the birds coming across from the south-east, behind Trimingham village, with some birds also passing over Hungry Hill rather than going along the coast. The birds frequently dropped into the pines briefly before continuing west, only two birds were seen actively seeking acorns in a small oak tree before moving on.  Also interesting that for a species usually so vociferous in woodland, the birds were silent on the move.  At the other corner of the north coast, Hunstanton scored with an impressive 668!  With the lack of any notable scandinavian/continental migrants here today (no winter thrushes at all) it is assumed the  majority of Jays currently being seen are British birds on the move due to the apparent failure of the acorn crop.
